    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-08-15T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-08-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="1014"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1014">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">622.116/120: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Long</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-08-15T00:00:00-05:00"
                            >August 15, 1940—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received August 16—5:32
                        p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>183. Referring to the Department’s telegram No. 110, August 12, 6 p.m.,
                    instructions have been given to Ecuadoran Consuls not to certify export
                    documents without previous permission of Director General of Exchange Control.
                    This is in line with exchange control regulations requiring advance
                    authorization for the purchase of exchange to cover new imports. See article IV,
                    Decree No. 130 reported in despatch No. 1153 of July 19.<note n="57"
                        xml:id="d1014fn1">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
